Introducing the Data

Dataset Info

The Set contains 14 different columns of information, ranging from different categories and data types.

Column Type
person_age Float

| person_gender | String | person_education |String | person_income | Float | | person_emp_exp | Integer | | person_home_ownership | String | | loan_amnt | Float | | loan_intent | String | | loan_int_rate | Float | | loan_percent_income | Float | | cb_person_cred_hist_length | Float | | credit_score | Integer | | previous_loan_defaults_on_file | String | | loan_status | Integer |

What are we trying to answer

The Key Question we want to answer is

  • Can a Machine Learning Model predict Predict whether a loan applicant will be approved based on financial history.

While also looking at:

  • Does having a positive or negative credit history impact the likelihood of a loan?
  • Which feature or features have the most influence on whether a loan is approved?

Scrubbing and Cleaning the Data

Before we do any type of analysis, we need to make sure the data is good for us to use. First we want to make sure there aren't any null values or any sort of unnecessary information.

The first thing we do is drop any missing values from the dataset. This can lead to some major issues for us in the future when analyzing and can lead to inconsistencies with our model later.

Encoding the Data

We need to decide the data where the different categorys in values to help determine what can result to the final loan result.

To do this we convert the variables to a different format into different coluumns. For example, person_gender is registered as male or female, but we need to convert this to a value which we can understand within the code. This is true for other columns as well.

In[135]:
categorical_columns = ['person_gender', 'person_education', 'person_home_ownership', 'loan_intent', 'previous_loan_defaults_on_file']
LoanDF_Encoded = pd.get_dummies(LoanDf, columns=categorical_columns, drop_first=True)

Splitting and Training the Dataset

To Split and train the data we want to include everything but the loan_status into the x and y will be the feature we will be testing for.

In[137]:
x = LoanDF_Encoded.drop('loan_status', axis=1)
y = LoanDF_Encoded['loan_status']

x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size=.3, random_state=42);

Lets Talk Modeling

For modeling our data we will be taking a look at 2 different algorithms we will be using for classification.

  • Logistic Regression
    • A binary classification algorithm that is able to predict the probability of certain classes based on features.
  • Random Forest
    • Builds many different decision trees and combines outputs. Trained on random subsets of the data, and then the final prediction is a majority rules scenario.

Logistic Regression

For this section, Ill be using Logistic Regression to predict wheather an application is accepted or not. We will be using the Testing data set which will be 70% training and 30% testing.

In[138]:
logreg = LogisticRegression()
logreg.fit(x_train, y_train)
y_pred_logreg = logreg.predict(x_test)
print("Logistic Regression Results:")
print(f"Accuracy score: {accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_logreg)}")

Logistic Regression Results:
Accuracy score: 0.8418518518518519

Classification Report & Confusion Matrix

The classificaition report showcases a 84% accuracy showing that it is majority of the time it is accurate, but still has room for error.

In[139]:
report_df = pd.DataFrame(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_logreg, output_dict=True))

report_df = report_df.drop(['support', 'accuracy'], errors='ignore')
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.heatmap(report_df, annot=True, cmap="Blues", fmt=".2f")
plt.title("Classification Report Heatmap - Logistic Regression")
plt.show()

cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_logreg)
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues')
plt.xlabel("Predicted Label")
plt.title("Confusion Matrix - Logistic Regression")
plt.show()

Feature Importance

Here we can see that the most important feature was looking at if the applier had previous loan defaults. Unlike others feature_importances_ doesnt seem to function here. So the graph is going to look different compared to one we see further below.

In[140]:
feature_names = x_train.columns.tolist()
coefficients = logreg.coef_[0]
feature_importance = pd.DataFrame({ 'Feature': feature_names, 'Coefficient': coefficients, 'absolutevaluecoes': abs(coefficients) })
feature_importance = feature_importance.sort_values('absolutevaluecoes', ascending=False)
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
sns.barplot( x='Coefficient', y='Feature', data=feature_importance.head(5),)
plt.title('Logistic Regression Feature Importance (Top 5)')
plt.ylabel('Feature')
plt.show()

Random Forest

For this section, I implement a Random Forest Classifier.

In[141]:
rf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
rf.fit(x_train, y_train)
y_pred_rf = rf.predict(x_test)
print("\nRandom Forest Results:")
print(f"Accuracy score: {accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_rf)}")

Random Forest Results:
Accuracy score: 0.926074074074074

Classification Report & Confusion Matrix

The classification report showcases a 93% accuracy showing that is majority of the time it is accurate, but still has room for error. This is better than what we have gotten from Linear Regression.

Evaluation

Looking at the models, we can see that Random Forest provided the best accuracy score at 92%. Each model evaluated apon its classification report.

Key Takeaways

  • Previous Loans Play a Major Role
    • From the Feature Importance that we have done for both models it showcases that if an applicant had previously defaulted on a loan then it matters the most.
  • Each Model has Mis-Classifications
    • In Each model, there are several inaccurate measures. There is not a 100% way to determine what allows you to receive an accepted application.

When taking a look at the initial question we set out to find Can a Machine Learning Model predict Predict whether a loan applicant will be approved based on financial history.. We can determine that while it is not 100%, it is close.

We can see that features did impact the loan approval process but, varies case by case. We also have to consider Human Interaction with the applicants. Different people handle loan applicants and sometimes make decisions on their own regardless of the details and information presented in front of them.

Impacts

Positive Impact

  1. Faster Applications
    • With the use of the model you can speed up the loan approval process by automating the procedure. This can lead
  2. Data-Driven Decisions
    • This model can lead to decisions that are more accurate and consistent. Driving out any external bias that could lead a great candidate to be denied.
  3. Risk Mitigation
    • The model helps identify high-risk applications faster and earlier than it could be detected normally.

Negative Impact

  1. Potential Bias
    • The training data could contain biases as these loan approvals need to be done.
  2. False Positives and Negatives
    • The model is not 100% accurate due to fluctuating factors, this can clead to incorrectly approving high risk applicatns or deny applications who are meant to recieve loans due to their history.
  3. Humans
    • The model loses the humility of the selection in complex or edge cases where the answer may not be a clear definitive yes or no.
